<DOC><DOCNO> AP890706-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 2316EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Korea-CopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0747 07-06 0372</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea-Copter Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0381</SECOND><HEAD>American Soldier Killed in Copter Crach, Korean Killed at FiringRange</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of helicopter crash and death,injuries at firing range; no pickup.</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter crashedeast of Seoul on Thursday night, killing one U.S. soldier andinjuring two others, U.S. military officials said.   The military also said a Korean civilian was killed and twoothers injured Thursday while U.S. troops were training at a firingrange.   The helicopter was on a routine night training mission when itcrashed about 10 p.m. Thursday about 8{ miles east of Seoul,according to a statement the military issued Friday.   It said the cause of the crash was under investigation.   The Korean newspaper Hankook Ilbo, quoting witnesses, said theaircraft went down when its blades hit a high voltage power lineabout 500 yards above the ground.   A unidentified Korean civilian was burned and slightly injuredwhen he tried to pull the injured soldiers from the fiery wreckage,witnesses said.   The names of the dead and injured were expected to be releasedlater in the day after their families were notified, a militaryspokesman said.   The aircraft belonged to the 2nd Infantry Division's 2ndBattalion, 2nd Aviation, according to the statement. The 2ndInfantry Division is the only U.S. infantry unit stationed in SouthKorea and includes about 15,000 troops.   The death and injuries at the firing range also involved unitsfrom the 2nd Infantry and occurred about 1{ miles south of thedemilitarized zone that separates communist North Korea from SouthKorea, a military spokesman said on condition of anonymity.   The spokesman said no Americans were hurt.   A military statement said the accident occurred during a routinetraining mission while units were using artillery fire. Thespokesman said the firing range is surrounded by a buffer zone thatis off-limits to civilians.   South Korean and U.S. military authorities were investigating,according to the statement.   The injured Koreans, flown to the 121st Evacuation Hospital atthe 8th U.S. Army Headquarters in Seoul, were identified as ChoNam-min, 73, and Shin Dong-sun, 71. Mrs. Shin was treated andreleased.   The name of the dead person was not released.</TEXT></DOC>